ber these paths for the build/test phases\n55\t\n56\t### Exploration Budget\n57\t\n58\tSpend **max 10-15 tool calls** on exploration before writing code. If `progress.txt` has a **Codebase Patterns** section, trust it ÔÇö only explore patterns not already documented there. Prior iterations documented patterns specifically to prevent redundant exploration. Each iteration re-exploring from scratch is the #1 cause of wasted context.\n59\t\n60\t### Phase 2: Implement\n61\t\n62\t7. Pick the **highest-priority** story where `passes: false`\n63\t8. Implement that story\n64\t9. Run **all** quality checks ÔÇö build, full test suite, lint. Verify zero regressions.\n65\t\n66\t### Phase 3: Record & Commit\n67\t\n68\t10. Update nearby `CLAUDE.md` files with any reusable patterns you discovered (see guidelines below)\n69\t11. Update `$PRD_DIR/prd.json` ÔÇö set `passes: true` for the completed story\n70\t12. Append to `$PRD_DIR/progress.txt` (see format below)\n71\t13. Commit (see commit procedure below)\n72\t\n73\t### Phase 4: Stop\n74\t\n75\t14. **You are done.** Reply with `<promise>COMPLETE</promise>` if every story now has `passes: true`. Otherwise, **end your session silently.** Another iteration will pick up the next story. Do NOT continue to the next story.\n76\t\n77\t---\n78\t\n79\t## Commit Procedure\n80\t\n81\tExtract the Jira ticket number from the branch name (pattern: `FMFX-XXXXX_description`).\n82\t\n83\tRun this exact sequence from the **repository root**:\n84\t\n85\t```bash\n86\tcd \"$(git rev-parse --show-toplevel)\"\n87\tgit add -A\n88\tgit status          # verify nothing unstaged/untracked\n89\tgit diff --cached --stat   # verify only expected files changed\n90\tgit commit -m \"feat(FMFX-XXXXX): concise description\"\n91\t```\n92\t\n93\tIf `git status` still shows unstaged/untracked files after `git add -A`, run it again until the working tree is clean. Do not commit until it is.\n94\t\n95\tUse conventional commit format:\n96\t\n97\t- `feat(FMFX-XXXXX): description` for new functionality\n98\t- `fix(FMFX-XXXXX): description` for bug fixes\n99\t\n100\t---\n101\t\n102\t## Build Strategy\n103\t\n104\tBuilding inside the sandbox uses virtiofs (Docker's host-to-container file sharing). This is fragile and almost always fails with MSB3248 errors. **Always rsync first.**\n105\t\n106\t1. **New projects MUST be in the solution file.** If you created or added new `.csproj` files, they won't build unless they're in `*.slnx` (or `*.sln`). Check with:\n107\t   ```bash\n108\t   grep 'YourNewProject' *.slnx  # or *.sln\n109\t   ```\n110\t   If missing, run `dotnet sln add path/to/Project.csproj` **before** building. Building without this wastes 4+ minutes on a build you'll have to redo.\n111\t2. **Always copy sources before building:**\n112\t   ```bash\n113\t   REPO_ROOT=\"$(git rev-parse --show-toplevel)\"\n114\t   rsync -a --exclude='.git' --exclude='bin' --exclude='obj' --exclude='.claude/projects' \"$REPO_ROOT/\" /tmp/build/\n115\t   cd /tmp/build && dotnet build --configuration Release /p:NetCoreBuild=true\n116\t   ```\n117\t3. **Never `cp -r` the entire repo.** This copies `.git`, `bin`, `obj` and causes OOM kills.\n118\t4. **After building in `/tmp/build`**, run tests from there too ÔÇö but commit from the original repo root.\n119\t5. **MinVer warnings (MINVER1001) are expected** when building in `/tmp/build` because `.git` is excluded. Ignore them.\n120\t6. **Skip rsync if only `tasks/` changed.** If `git diff --name-only` since last build shows only `tasks/**` (PRD/progress) or other non-source files, do NOT rsync ÔÇö `/tmp/build` is already correct. Rsync of the full repo costs ~1 minute.\n121\t7. **On a warm `/tmp/build`, prefer `--no-restore` + project filter.** After a successful full-solution build, subsequent compiles of the same iteration can skip restore: `cd /tmp/build && timeout 300 dotnet build src/YourModule/Application/Application.csproj --configuration Release --no-restore`.\n122\t8. **Do NOT rebuild `HostApp` just to re-verify after your project builds clean.** `HostApp` pulls private GitHub Packages (`Freemarket.Persistence.Blob` etc.) that fail with `NU1301` in the sandbox ÔÇö this is a known auth limitation, not a regression. If your changed project builds, stop.\n123\t\n124\t### StyleCop Pre-Check (before every build)\n125\t\n126\tBefore running `dotnet build`, scan every `.cs` file you modified for common violations. Fix auto-fixable ones in-place, report manual-fix ones in progress.txt.\n127\t\n128\t**Identify targets:**\n129\t```bash\n130\tgit diff --name-only main...HEAD -- '*.cs'\n131\t```\n132\t\n133\t**Auto-fix these (edit the file directly):**\n134\t- **SA1210**: Reorder `using` directives alphabetically (`System.*` first)\n135\t- **SA1413**: Add trailing comma to last element in multi-line initializers/enums\n136\t- **SA1512**: Remove blank line immediately after a `//` comment\n137\t- **SA1513**: Closing brace must be followed by a blank line ÔÇö and a closing brace must NOT be followed by an extra blank line. After Edits, scan for `}\\n\\n\\n` (extra blank) and `}\\n[^\\n}]` (missing blank before next member) on modified files.\n138\t- **IDE1006**: Private fields must be `_camelCase` (prefix with `_`)\n139\t\n140\t**Check and report only (do NOT auto-reorder):**\n141\t- **SA1202**: Public members must appear before private members\n142\t- **SA1203**: Constants must appear before non-constant fields\n143\t- **SA1214**: Readonly fields must appear before non-readonly fields\n144\t- **SA1128**: Constructor initializer (`: base(...)`) must be on its own line\n145\t- **SA1502**: Class/method body must not be on a single line (except `=>` members)\n146\t- **SA1117**: Parameters split across lines must each be on their own line\n147\t\n148\tIf manual-fix violations are found, note them in progress.txt under the current story.\n149\t\n150\tDo NOT skip this step ÔÇö run it before every `dotnet build`.\n151\t\n152\t### Build & Test Execution Rules\n153\t\n154\t**CRITICAL: Never run build+test as a single compound or background command.** Run each step as a separate foreground Bash call so you can inspect results and react to failures:\n155\t\n156\t```bash\n157\t# Step 1: rsync\n158\trsync -a --exclude='.git' --exclude='bin' --exclude='obj' --exclude='.claude/projects' \"$REPO_ROOT/\" /tmp/build/\n159\t\n160\t# Step 2: build (separate call, foreground, WITH TIMEOUT)\n161\tcd /tmp/build && timeout 600 dotnet build --configuration Release /p:NetCoreBuild=true\n162\t\n163\t# Step 3: test (separate call, foreground, with timeout)\n164\tcd /tmp/build && timeout 300 dotnet test --configuration Release --no-build\n165\t```\n166\t\n167\t- **Never chain rsync, build, and test with `&&` in a single command.** If the build fails you waste the entire test timeout waiting.\n168\t- **Never use background tasks (`run_in_background`) for build or test.** Background tasks + `TaskOutput(block:true)` create a deadlock if the command hangs ÔÇö you cannot intervene, cancel, or inspect partial output.\n169\t- **Always use `timeout 600` (10 min) on `dotnet build` and `timeout 300` (5 min) on `dotnet test`.** If a build hasn't finished in 10 minutes or tests in 5 minutes, something is hung. Kill it and investigate rather than waiting for the outer timeout.\n170\t- **If a test run times out**, check whether TestContainers is trying to pull a Docker image that isn't available in the sandbox. Skip those tests and note them for CI.\n171\t\n172\t### If a build or test is killed (exit code 143)\n173\t\n174\tExit 143 = SIGTERM (timeout or outer kill). Do NOT retry the exact same full-solution build. Instead:\n175\t1. Check if `/tmp/build` still has the rsync'd sources ÔÇö if so, skip rsync\n176\t2. Build only the changed project first: `cd /tmp/build && timeout 300 dotnet build src/YourModule/Application/Application.csproj --configuration Release`\n177\t3. If that passes, attempt the full solution build\n178\t4. If the full build keeps timing out, commit what you have (rule 6) and note the issue in progress.txt\n179\t\n180\t### Testing in the sandbox\n181\t\n182\t- **Use discovered test paths.** Use the test project paths you found in Phase 1 step 6. Do NOT hardcode template names like `Module.Tests`.\n183\t- **Run all tests by default.** Filter syntax is unreliable in the sandbox ÔÇö `--filter-class`, `--filter-method`, and `--filter` all fail with some test runners. Prefer running the full suite:\n184\t  ```bash\n185\t  cd /tmp/build && timeout 300 dotnet test --configuration Release --no-build\n186\t  ```\n187\t  If you must filter, try `dotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~ClassName\"` as a best-effort fallback ÔÇö but don't spend more than one attempt if it fails.\n188\t- **Cosmos emulator does NOT work in the sandbox.** The Docker image is too large to pull reliably through the sandbox network proxy. Skip Cosmos-dependent tests and defer them to CI. Only run SQL-based tests.\n189\t- **SQL Server (TestContainers) works** ÔÇö MCR images for SQL Server pull successfully.\n190\t- **Always rsync the full repo, not individual app subdirectories.** Projects have cross-repo NuGet/build dependencies that break with partial copies.\n191\t- **Config/test fixture coupling:** When adding config dependencies to a module's `Configuration` class (e.g., `config.GetRequiredSection(\"Sql\")`), always update the corresponding test fixture to provide that config section. Missing config in test fixtures causes `InvalidOperationException` at test time.\n192\t\n193\t---\n194\t\n195\t## Line Ending Discipline\n196\t\n197\tMost repos have `.gitattributes` with `* text=auto`, which means git normalises line endings on commit. Check for this first ÔÇö if present, you generally don't need to worry about CRLF.\n198\t\n199\tIf `.gitattributes` does NOT handle line endings:\n200\t\n201\t- Prefer `sed -i` for targeted edits ÔÇö it preserves line endings of untouched lines.\n202\t- If you rewrite an entire file, pipe through `unix2dos` before 